<font color="#FF0000">I'M ASKING - PLEASE TELL</font><br>
<tt>Thu Nov 28  1:08:31 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
I am asking.  <br><br>
I am asking to understand.  I don't care about the battles... the who did what and when.  I want to understand the emotions.  The sorrow.  I need to heal myself from the RESULTS.  I am only 35.  I have memories of TV news... body counts that never seemed quite real.  My family was against the war.  We participated in the demonstrations - though most of them I don't remember.  <br><br>
There is much that I am oblivious to.  Much I was unaware of due to my age.  Yet somehow this war, not just the one &quot;over there&quot; but the one that took place on Americian soil, tears at my soul.  I need to understand.  But I have found no one like Mr. Callahan (above)to ask.  No one near me wants to talk about it.  No one is willing to explain.  I have been unable to find someone who feels comfortable enough with a &quot;stranger&quot; to share.  The unwritten rule seems to be that this agony - this pain - is so intimate that only close friends can inquire.<br><br>
I have a sense that I have much to learn.  I don't know how to open the dialog.  I don't know how to ask.  Now, it seems that this site is doing some of the asking for me.  I will be back to read some of the answers.<br><br>
Thank you.
